estimates the volume of a 3D blob above a fitted baseline plane. The algorithm works by slicing the blob into thin height bands, calculating the 2D cross-sectional area of each slice, and summing the slice volumes.
Conceptually:
Total Volume ≈ Σ(slice area × slice thickness)

Algorithm goes through the following steps to estimate volume:
1. Validate input point cloud and baseline plane.
2. Normalize the baseline plane normal.
3. Build a local coordinate system aligned to the baseline plane.
4. Convert every point into local plane coordinates:
      u = local X on plane
      v = local Y on plane
      h = height above plane
5. Determine the maximum height of the blob.
6. Split the height range into slices.
7. For each slice:
      a. collect points whose height falls inside the slice
      b. remove radial XY outliers
      c. compute a 2D convex hull
      d. calculate hull area
      e. multiply area by slice thickness
      f. convert hull and centroid back to world coordinates
8. Sum all slice volume contributions.

The method does not calculate volume directly in world XYZ coordinates. Instead, it builds a local coordinate system based on the fitted baseline plane.

This is important because the baseline plane may be tilted relative to machine/world Z. Volume should be measured relative to the local surface plane, not blindly along world Z.


